<p>AU uses its carbon neutrality status in its branding, marketing and admissions campaigns. However, AU is carbon neutral on paper, rather than through physical practice. Instead of expanding and investing in on-campus resources, like solar panels, wind generation and other renewable energy methods, the University invested in a solar farm in North Carolina.</p>

<h2 id="how-au-got-the-title">How AU got the title</h2>

<p>Tacy Lambiase is the Sustainability Manager at AU‚Äôs Office of Sustainability. Among other things, she is one of many who oversee the sustainability agenda of the University and the community outreach of resources.</p>

<p>The data collection process to calculate the emissions includes an institutional survey.</p>

<p>‚ÄúWe do an annual inventory every year. To collect data, we calculate faculty, staff and students‚Äô emissions across campus. A portion of our community gets surveyed every year,‚Äù Lambiase said.</p>

<p>Then, the Office of Institutional Research calculates the percentages needed to survey the community, as well as the estimated target response rate for the community, Lambiase said.</p>

<p>The survey consists of a list of questions regarding personal emissions. For example, transportation needs like commute time or plane mileage for study abroad are questions in the survey.</p>

<p>‚ÄúWe are able to get a pretty good sense of how our community is emitting, and the implications related to that,‚Äù Lambiase said.</p>

<p>To become carbon neutral, the University needs to produce enough renewable energy or purchase offsets to achieve neutrality. There needs to be enough of these resources to exceed, or match, the campus carbon emissions.</p>

<p>There are multiple strategies used to achieve neutrality.</p>

<p>‚ÄúThe first is to reduce emissions as much as possible. The second is changing the sources of fuel on campus, like the University‚Äôs switch from steam to low temperature hot water,‚Äù Lambiase said.</p>

<p>The last method of zero net emissions includes a monetary investment.</p>

<p>‚ÄúAnd the third is investing in 100% renewable energy,‚Äù Lambiase said.</p>

<p>The budget for the purchases of RECs comes from the Facilities Management budget, according to Lambiase.</p>

<p>AU has to rely on such external methods for carbon neutrality investment due to limited campus space. In other words, AU does not have the physical space to provide solar and wind resources to overcome the campus electricity and power needs, Lambiase said.</p>

<p>Since AU is an urban campus and doesn‚Äôt have the space to build entire farms, they built an off-campus solar farm in <a href="https://wjla.com/news/local/george-washington-university-american-university-make-deal-to-buy-solar-power-farms--104425">North Carolina</a>. The entire farm contains a quarter of a million solar panels, but the output of these meets only 50% of the campus electricity needs.</p>

<p>‚ÄúThe energy that is generated by those solar panels is going to the local North Carolina grid. The energy goes to those communities‚Ä¶they are not directly traveling to D.C.,‚Äù Lambiase said.</p>

<p>In addition to these solar and wind farms, RECs are purchased to help offset the energy coming from D.C.‚Äôs energy grid.</p>

<p>Part of this investment also includes on-campus renewables, such as the solar panels on 10 of AU‚Äôs rooftops.</p>

<p>‚ÄúWe are looking to expand that,‚Äù Lambiase said. 
It‚Äôs important to note that, despite the 2,500 panels located across campus, it only covers half of a percent of the campus needs, Lambiase said.</p>

<p>Carbon neutrality comes from this plethora of emission resources and solutions. However, it does not allow AU to hold the most carbon-neutral school in America. AU has not claimed such a title but holds the ‚Äúfirst large campus and the first university to become carbon neutral,‚Äù according to Second Nature.</p>

<p>This makes some students skeptical of AU‚Äôs sustainability commitment.</p>

<p>Some students are concerned with the greenwash effect. <a href="https://www.investopedia.com/terms/g/greenwashing.asp">Greenwashing</a> is the phenomenon or the practice of ‚Äúmaking unwarranted or overblown claims of sustainability or environmental friendliness in an attempt to gain market share,‚Äù according to Environmental Health Perspectives.</p>

<h2 id="how-does-au-measure-up-in-the-us">How does AU measure up in the U.S.?</h2>

<p>Since 2018, the EPA archives the <a href="https://www.epa.gov/greenpower/green-power-partnership-top-30-college-university-pdfs">top 30</a> carbon neutral colleges in America, on an almost quarterly basis.</p>

